pwd - This command is used to show the current working directory.
pwd -L - This command is used to show the logical path of the current working directory.
pwd -R - This command is used to show the physical path of the current working directory.
=-help - It shows the help message.
--version - it provides the program version.
cd ~ or cd  - by itself will always bring the user to the home directory.
cd . -  will allow the user to stay in the similar directory they are in currently.
cd - will change the user to the old directory.
ls -a -  The (ls -a) command will enlist the whole list of the current directory including the hidden files.
ls -l  - It will show the list in a long list format.
ls -lh -  This command will show you the file sizes in human readable format. 
ls -lhS  - If you want to display your files in descending order (highest at the top) according to their size, then you can use (ls -lhS) command.
ls -n  - It is used to print group ID and owner ID instead of their names.
ls -r  - It is used to print the list in reverse order.
ls -R - It will display the content of the sub-directories also.
ls --version It checks the version of ls command.
whoami - It tells you about the system's username.
who -  The who command gives the information about the users logged on to the system.
w - This command tells about the users who are logged in and what are they doing.




